T1  - Cricketing Multiculturalism in Caryl Phillips's Playing Away
AN  - 1266146836; 201301548
AB  - This essay explores the critique of 1980s' multiculturalism in Caryl Phillips's 1986 screenplay Playing Away, which depicts a cricket match held between a black British team from Brixton and the well-to-do white villagers of the fictional town of Sneddington. It proceeds by considering Phillips's long-standing commitment to sport as an opportunity where new social and cultural relations can be built which question established prejudices and divisions, captured in the notion of 'sporting tribalry', before turning to a close engagement with the film's key elements. Rather than depict two teams, one black and urban, the other white and rural, at loggerheads both on and off the cricket pitch, Playing Away attends to the many overlappings and similarities shared across communities that are discerned as a way of challenging prevailing models of multicultural difference. Phillips shows how these shared challenges may bring communities together through 'sporting tribalry', where they might learn from each other and move forward from entrenched and divisive notions of difference or 'race relations'. Ultimately, the remoulded model of multiculturalism suggested by Playing Away exists more as a promise than an achieved reality: as is indicated by the vexed cricket match between the teams which forms the climax of the film, the tensions of class, culture, race and gender are not easily erased in the late 1980s. Adapted from the source document.
